Splits the collection into two at the given index.

Returns a newly allocated vector containing the elements in the range `[at, len)`. After the call, the original vector will be left containing the elements `[0, at)` with its previous capacity unchanged.

-   If you want to take ownership of the entire contents and capacity of the vector, see [`mem::take`](../mem/fn.take.html "fn std::mem::take") or [`mem::replace`](../mem/fn.replace.html "fn std::mem::replace").
-   If you don‚Äôt need the returned vector at all, see [`Vec::truncate`](about:blank/struct.Vec.html#method.truncate "method std::vec::Vec::truncate").
-   If you want to take ownership of an arbitrary subslice, or you don‚Äôt necessarily want to store the removed items in a vector, see [`Vec::drain`](about:blank/struct.Vec.html#method.drain "method std::vec::Vec::drain").

##### [¬ß](#panics-10)Panics

Panics if `at > len`.

##### [¬ß](#examples-39)Examples

```
