1.31.0 ¬∑ [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/slice/mod.rs.html#1214)

Returns an iterator over `chunk_size` elements of the slice at a time, starting at the beginning of the slice.

The chunks are slices and do not overlap. If `chunk_size` does not divide the length of the slice, then the last up to `chunk_size-1` elements will be omitted and can be retrieved from the `remainder` function of the iterator.

Due to each chunk having exactly `chunk_size` elements, the compiler can often optimize the resulting code better than in the case of [`chunks`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.chunks "method slice::chunks").

See [`chunks`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.chunks "method slice::chunks") for a variant of this iterator that also returns the remainder as a smaller chunk, and [`rchunks_exact`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.rchunks_exact "method slice::rchunks_exact") for the same iterator but starting at the end of the slice.

##### [¬ß](#panics-20)Panics

Panics if `chunk_size` is 0.

##### [¬ß](#examples-87)Examples

```
let slice = ['l', 'o', 'r', 'e', 'm'];
let mut iter = slice.chunks_exact(2);
assert_eq!(iter.next().unwrap(), &['l', 'o']);
assert_eq!(iter.next().unwrap(), &['r', 'e']);
assert!(iter.next().is_none());
assert_eq!(iter.remainder(), &['m']);
```

